article.description: Nykesha Sales scored five of her 19 points in the final 1:15 to lead the Sun over the Shock 74-72 Sunday.
article.headline: Sales leads Sun with 19 points
article.linkText: Sun nip Shock for back-to-back sweep
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Nykesha Sales was again too much for
the Detroit Shock.

She scored five of her 19 points in the final 1:15 to help the
Connecticut Sun beat Detroit 74-72 Sunday, the second time they've
beaten the Shock in three days.

Wendy Palmer added 18 points to help send her former team to its
third loss in four games. Connecticut has beaten the defending WNBA
champs twice in a row after losing seven in a row to them,
including a two-game sweep in the playoffs last season.

"We realized that we can play with this team," Sales said.
"We understand that they won a championship last year, but this
year, other teams are hungry."

Lindsey Whalen, the fourth pick in April's draft, set a
franchise record with 13 assists to go with 10 points.

"That's why we got her in the draft," Connecticut coach Mike
Thibault said. "She doesn't care about scoring, and yet she made
two big threes when we needed them."

All-Star Cheryl Ford returned to the Detroit lineup after
missing three games for her grandfather's funeral. She missed nine
of her first 10 field-goal attempts and did not score in the first
half, but finished with 15 points and 10 rebounds.

"I didn't have my timing, but I'm not going to blame last week
for that," she said. "My teammates had confidence in me and they
kept giving me the ball, and I got going."

Swin Cash led the Shock with 20 points and Ruth Riley added 18.

The Sun led by as many as 11 in the final 10 minutes, but six
straight points from Cash cut the margin to 69-68 with 1:49 left.
Katie Douglas missed a 3-pointer and Riley put Detroit back in
front with two free throws with 1:35 to play.

Sales answered with a 3-pointer with 1:15 left, then blocked
Riley's shot and scored a breakaway layup to put Connecticut up by
four.

Cash's layup made it 74-72 and Sales missed, giving Detroit the
ball with 6.7 seconds left. Chandi Jones missed a winning 3-pointer
and, while Cash got the rebound, she wasn't able to get a shot off
before the buzzer.

"It's not fun to keep losing by two points or four points,"
Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "It's the little things that we
aren't doing. We know we are a very good basketball team, but we
have to want to play like one."

Sales scored 22 points and matched a career high with 10
rebounds Friday night in Connecticut's overtime win.

On Sunday, the Shock led by as many as 14 in the first half, but
Connecticut had the margin down to 39-32 at the half.

"I think that was the key to the game," Sales said. "We were
down 12 or 13 and we silently came back and got close. That really
helped us."

The Sun then used a 17-2 run to take a 51-45 lead with 11:45 to
go. Palmer had eight points in the run and Whalen added five.

Detroit missed 13 of its first 16 shots in the second half
before Ford ended Connecticut's run with a layup. Sales, though,
hit a 3-pointer at the other end to increase the Connecticut margin
to seven points, 54-47.
